{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018PxAyj3e5Mo1WoAfV1mhDN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the setup. The precondition creates:\n1. A CA key and cert (`ca.key`, `ca.crt`)\n2. A server cert signed by that CA with a short validity (`old_cert_valid_days = 2 days`)\n3. The `mongodb-tls-ca` secret with `ca.crt` and `ca.key`\n4. The `mongodb-tls-cert` secret with `server.pem`\n5. A configmap `mongodb-tls-old` with fingerprints of the old certs\n6. The MongoDB StatefulSet is deployed\n\nBut the probe says `kubectl -n mongodb get pod mongo-rs-0 | grep -c Running` already exists (returned 1), so the precondition was skipped (it ran `probe` and it succeeded, so `apply` was skipped).\nSo the actual current state is different from what the precondition would have set up. There's a `mongo-tls` secret with `ca.crt`, `client.pem`, and `server.pem` already in place, the StatefulSet is running with all 3 replicas ready, and the cert in that secret doesn't expire until 2036. The `mongodb-tls-ca` and `mongodb-tls-cert` secrets that the precondition would have created don't actually exist.\n\nThis means there's a mismatch between what the certificate-rotation case expects to mount and what's actually deployed. I need to look at the StatefulSet definition in the certificate-rotation case to see what secrets it's trying to use, then compare that to what's currently running to understand the discrepancy.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3463,"cache_read_input_tokens":34707,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3463},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0656db3c-c9d4-4a0b-8d45-5c2a815a427e","uuid":"e1a55128-24f8-47ba-a914-54caf6b55