{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014pezE7BYHhydg3p3o456zo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n1. Stage 4 was `tls-setup` (PASSED) - this set up MongoDB with TLS using the `mongo-tls` secret\n2. Stage 5 is `certificate-rotation` - the precondition was SKIPPED (probe found mongo-rs-0 running), so the environment from `tls-setup` is still in place\n\nThe certificate-rotation precondition was supposed to tear down the existing MongoDB and set up a new one with the specific secret structure (mongodb-tls-ca, mongodb-tls-cert, mongodb-tls-old). But since it was skipped, the tls-setup environment is still running.\nNow I need to perform the certificate rotation itself. The Oracle validation checks for several things: the old CA fingerprint stored in a configmap, the new CA and server certificates in separate secrets with specific keys, that the CA fingerprint hasn't changed while the server cert has, the server cert validity window, and that TLS connections still work from within the pod. The main issue is that the current setup uses a single `mongo-tls` secret with a different mount structure than what the rotation expects.\n\nMy strategy is to treat the current environment as the baseline and perform a full rotation to match the expected structure. I'll generate a new CA along with both an expiring server cert and a fresh one in the openssl-toolbox, then create the `mongodb-tls-old` configmap to record the old server cert fingerprint, and set up the `mongodb-tls-ca` secret with the new CA certificate and key.\n\nI'll then create the `mongodb-tls-cert` secret with the new 365-day server certificate and update the StatefulSet to reference these new secrets at the correct mount paths while adjusting the MongoDB command arguments. The rolling restart will happen automatically, and while there's a brief window where some pods use the old CA and others use the new 